##The first death has occurred! ... Donald Trump was quick to point out that what beauty experts fear most may have happened.

On February 29, King County health officials in Seattle, Washington, reported that a 50-year-old male patient with new crown pneumonia died at a local hospital that day. This is the first death of a new case of pneumonia in the United States. Regarding the route of infection of the deceased, Nancy Messonnier, the CDC's director of National Immunization and respiratory disease, said there was no confirmation.

The patient had no previous travel history or exposure to a known source of infection, according to the report. Washington Governor Insley declared a state of emergency and said state agencies would use "all necessary resources" to prepare for a new outbreak, and authorize the use of the National Guard of the United States in Washington state if necessary.

In addition to the death, there were four new nucleic acid positive cases in the state of Washington, including two from staff and patients at the same care center in the State of Kings County, Kirkland. The paramedic, in his 40s, is in stable condition, while the patient, in his 70s, is in serious condition.

According to US media reports, the other two cases were a high school student with an unknown source of infection and a woman in her 50s who had travelled to Taegu, South Korea. So far, a total of 22 cases of NCP have been confirmed in the United States, 3 cases have been confirmed from the evacuees from Wuhan, China, and 44 cases have been confirmed from the evacuees from the "Diamond Princess" cruise ship in Japan, the total number of new coronary pneumonia cases in the United States has increased to 69.

US President Donald Trump held a press conference at the White House after the first death was reported, saying the US would issue more travel bans to stop further transmission of the new coronavirus. In addition, he will discuss with the head of the pharmaceutical industry to develop a new coronavirus vaccine. But Donald Trump stressed that there was no need for the American public to panic and that the risk posed by the new coronavirus remained low for the average American.

Donald Trump also spoke highly of the Chinese government's efforts to contain the epidemic and sought cooperation, CCTV news reported.

U.S. EXPERT: Risk of epidemic spreading increases

So far, four confirmed cases of COVID-19 infection of unknown origin have been identified in the United States, the Global Times reported, citing U.S. media.

Earlier, Sarah, director of Public Health at the Santa Clara County in California, told reporters of cases from unknown sources in the area, "This new case is evidence of ongoing community transmission, but the extent is not clear... I know this news may be alarming, but we have been preparing for it. Now we need to start taking other actions to slow the spread of the virus."

However, epidemiologist, of the Rand Corporation, said the number of cases of community based transmission in the United States had shown that a travel ban alone could not stop the spread of the virus. She suggested that, with local transmission already in place, the United States should now focus on whether hospitals have sufficient capacity to take patients, test for adequate reagents, and speed up the training of health care workers, to improve its ability to screen for suspicious symptoms.

"training in health care to identify new coronavirus infections has been underway in the United States for some time, and state health authorities have been preparing for it, " Wong said, adding that the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has also updated its testing standards, no longer will having a Chinese travel history be one of the requirements for acceptable testing.

But more needs to be done. "whether or not to use a designated hospital, how to isolate patients with mild illness when the hospital capacity is insufficient, and how to transport patients safely have all become matters that need to be considered and prepared immediately in the United States, " she said.

According to CNN, the community spread of nucleic acid detection in the United States has encountered great challenges. CDC Director of the respiratory disease, Nancy Maisonier 28, acknowledged that the initial sent to state and local laboratories of some detection kits defects, reducing the ability to detect new coronaviruses around. With the exception of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, only a handful of laboratories can perform the tests.

Earlier, California's governor, Gavin Newsom, had complained publicly that the state's few hundred test kits were inadequate to deal with the current problems. In this case, the United States has been improving the nucleic acid detection capacity as one of the main work. By the end of the week, 93 laboratories across the country are expected to have test capabilities, said Alex Azar, the US Health Secretary.

"The U.S. is officially open for business, " says Chen Xi, an assistant professor of global health policy and economics at Yale. Large cities have large numbers of people without health insurance, while large rural areas are less at risk.

HOUSTON, N95 face masks are up in price

Despite Donald Trump's downplaying of the outbreak and the CDC's recommendation that the public not wear face masks, Americans don't seem to be buying it. CNN reported that many people in the United States have queued up to buy masks and other supplies. 100 packs of 4,533 dust masks, which originally sold for $8 a pack, have sold for $200 a pack in some places.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Donald Trump administration is reportedly considering using the defense production act to boost the country's rapidly expanding supply of face masks, protective clothing and other anti epidemic assets to address the high demand for face masks. The law was passed by Congress in 1950 during the outbreak of the Korean War.

The law gives the president the power to expand the production of critical materials or products for reasons of national security. The report quoted officials as saying that the U. S. is currently in short supply of protective materials. Using the law is one of several options the U. S. government is considering.

Tuesday, HHS Secretary of Alex Azar, told a Congressional hearing that the nation currently has a strategic stockpile of 30 million N95 masks, but U.S. health care workers need as many as 300 million.

On the same day, Nancy Maisonier, director of the respiratory disease at the CDC, said that as more countries and regions are experiencing community transmission, it is becoming increasingly difficult to contain the spread of the virus within the United States. "It's not a question of if, it's a question of when, " Meisner said.

Chen Xi, an assistant professor of Global Health Policy and economics at Yale, said CDC guidelines for face masks should not be "one size fits all. ". Under current circumstances, in densely populated cities such as New York and Washington, people should wear masks. He also said that the United States, which relies on imports from China for most of its face masks, could face a severe shortage of medical supplies in the future due to the massive trade disruption caused by the outbreak.

Chen Xi also said that the public health now officially plans to jointly advise the White House and President Donald Trump on policy, but that the current debate in the public health community is whether school closures are necessary in some areas, there is no consensus among health experts on the issue.
